# Project One: Network Reconfiguration
**CYB-210 | Computer Networking | Grade: A**

## Objective
Reconfigure an existing network in Cisco Packet Tracer to implement proper segmentation, a guest wireless network, isolated device groups, and a separate camera network — all following security best practices.

---

## A. VLAN Configuration
Configured VLANs to logically separate network traffic by function. VLANs allow devices on the same physical switch to be isolated from each other — a core security control that limits lateral movement in the event of a compromise.

**Why VLANs matter for security:** Without segmentation, a compromised device has direct access to every other device on the network. VLANs enforce boundaries at the network layer.

---

## B. Guest Wireless Network
Set up an isolated guest wireless network (FREE_WIRELESS) separate from the main LAN. Guest devices receive IPs from a dedicated DHCP scope and cannot access internal resources.

**Security consideration:** Guest networks must be fully isolated — shared credentials or bridged access to the internal network defeats the purpose entirely.

---

## C. Device Reconfiguration
Reorganized device placement across the network to ensure each device type (workstations, printers, IoT) exists in its appropriate segment with only the access it needs.

**Principle applied:** Least Privilege at the network level — devices only have connectivity to the resources required for their function.

---

## D. Camera Network Segmentation
Added a separate network segment dedicated to security cameras. Camera traffic is isolated from employee workstations and administrative systems.

**Why this matters:** IoT and camera devices are frequent attack targets due to weak default credentials and infrequent patching. Isolating them limits the damage if one is compromised.

---

## E. Network Segregation — Explanation
Proper network segregation creates security boundaries that:
- Limit the blast radius of any single compromised device
- Prevent unauthorized lateral movement between segments
- Allow granular monitoring and access control per segment
- Meet compliance requirements for sensitive data environments (e.g., separating payment systems, health records, or classified data)

